The '''Symphony No. 3''' by [[Aram Khachaturian]], subtitled '''Symphony–Poem''', was composed in 1947 for the 30th anniversary of the [[Russian Revolution]], and premiered on [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]] on December&nbsp;13 by the [[Leningrad Philharmonic]] conducted by [[Yevgeny Mravinsky]].<ref>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2007/Aug07/KHACHATURIAN_Melcd1001006.htm Review of Melodiya's MPO/Kondrashin release by Rob Barnett] in musicweb-international.com</ref> It was his last contribution to the genre. Originally conceived as a [[symphonic poem]], it is a single movement symphony featuring an organ solo and fifteen trumpets conceived as a hymn of praise of the [[Soviet Union]], with Khachaturian saying that he "wanted this work to express the Soviet people’s joy and pride in their great and mighty country".<ref>[http://www.cantonsymphony.org/312 Program notes by Tom Wachunas] in the [[Canton Symphony Orchestra|Canton Symphony]]'s website</ref> However, the work's raw and strident style, which has been related to the 1920s Soviet [[Constructivism (art)|constructivist]] [[avantgarde]],<ref>Commentary on the composition in Guide de la Musique Symphonique by F.R. de Tranchefort et al., page 392</ref> and unorthodox structure and instrumentation dissatisfied the [[Stalin]]ist [[Union of Soviet Composers|cultural authorities]], and it was condemned as [[formalism (music)|formalistic]] in the 1948 [[Zhdanov decree]].
==Discography== * [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]] – [[Leopold Stokowski]]. [[RCA Red Seal]], 1969. * [[Moscow Philharmonic]] – [[Kirill Kondrashin]], G. Grodberg, organist. [[Melodiya]], date unknown? (ca.1960s?)<ref>{{OCLC|38181847}}.</ref> * [[Leningrad Philharmonic]] – [[Evgeny Mravinsky]]. [[Melodiya]], 1983. * [[Armenian Philharmonic Orchestra|Armenian Philharmonic]] – [[Loris Tjeknavorian]]. [[ASV Records|ASV]], 1993. * [[BBC Philharmonic]] – [[Fedor Glushchenko]]. [[Chandos Records|Chandos]], 1993.<ref>{{OCLC|32710586}}. Issued 1994.</ref>
