{{Infobox book | name = The Hare with Amber Eyes | image = The Hare with Amber Eyes (Edmund de Waal novel) cover art.jpg | caption = | author = [[Edmund de Waal]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[Ephrussi family]] | genre = [[Biography]] | publisher = Farrar, Straus and Giroux | pub_date = 2010 | media_type = | pages = 353 | isbn = 978-0-374-10597-6 | oclc = 694399313 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} [[File:Hare with Amber Eyes (1).jpg|thumb|The Hare with Amber Eyes ''[[netsuke]]'', at an exhibition in the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] Vienna, November 2016]] '''''The Hare with Amber Eyes''''' (2010) is a family memoir by British ceramicist [[Edmund de Waal]].<ref name="unheard of Jewish family">[http://thejewishchronicle.net/view/full_story/15401716/article--Hare--chronicles-unheard-of-Jewish-family?instance=news_special_coverage_right_column 'Hare' chronicles unheard of Jewish family], [[The Jewish Chronicle of Pittsburgh]] (6 September 2011)</ref> De Waal tells the story of his family, the [[Ephrussi family|Ephrussi]], once a very wealthy European Jewish banking dynasty, centered in [[Odessa]], [[Vienna]] and [[Paris]], and peers of the [[Rothschild family]].<ref name="unheard of Jewish family"/> The Ephrussis lost almost everything in 1938 when the Nazis [[Aryanization (Nazism)|aryanized]] their property.<ref name="unheard of Jewish family"/> Even after the war, the family failed to recover most of its extensive property, including priceless artwork, but an easily hidden collection of 264 Japanese [[netsuke]] miniature sculptures was saved, tucked away inside a mattress by Anna, a loyal maid at [[Palais Ephrussi]] in Vienna during the war years. The collection has been passed down through five generations of the Ephrussi family, providing a common thread for the story of its fortunes from 1871 to 2009.
